  <rdf:Description rdf:about="http://poi-kb.org/ards/hasRiskFactor">
    <rdf:type rdf:resource="http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#ObjectProperty"/>
    <rdfs:label xml:lang="en">has risk factor</rdfs:label>
    <rdfs:comment xml:lang="en">Disease has the referenced risk factor contributing to its development. OBO: RO:0002410. Corresponds to BioLink biolink:contributes_to (inverse).</rdfs:comment>
    <obo:hasDbXref>biolink:contributes_to</obo:hasDbXref>
    <obo:hasDbXref>RO:0003303</obo:hasDbXref>
  </rdf:Description>
  <rdf:Description rdf:about="http://poi-kb.org/ards/ARDS_POI_03200">
    <rdf:type rdf:resource="http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#Class"/>
    <rdfs:label xml:lang="en">Hyperinflammatory ARDS subphenotype</rdfs:label>
    <obo:inSubset rdf:resource="http://poi-kb.org/ards/POI_disease"/>
    <obo:IAO_0000115 xml:lang="en">Biologically distinct ARDS subphenotype identified by latent class analysis (Calfee et al. AJRCCM 2014; PMID 25030514). Characterised by elevated plasma IL-6 (&gt;400 pg/mL), IL-8, sRAGE, angiopoietin-2, PAI-1; vasopressor-dependent shock; metabolic acidosis; higher 90-day mortality. Differential response to higher PEEP compared to hypoinflammatory subphenotype. Heterogeneity of treatment effect (HTE): conservative fluid management associated with improved outcomes (lower PEEP may worsen; moderate-high PEEP may benefit). Possible immunomodulation benefit (baricitinib, dexamethasone). Real-time classification feasible using parsimonious 3-variable model (IL-8, Protein C, bicarbonate) without requiring full biomarker panel (Sinha 2020 PMID:32461733; Gao 2021; Calfee 2014 PMID:25030514).</obo:IAO_0000115>
    <obo:hasExactSynonym xml:lang="en">Hyperinflammatory phenotype</obo:hasExactSynonym>
    <obo:hasExactSynonym xml:lang="en">Reactive ARDS</obo:hasExactSynonym>
    <obo:hasExactSynonym xml:lang="en">Type H ARDS</obo:hasExactSynonym>
    <obo:hasExactSynonym xml:lang="en">ARDS subphenotype 2</obo:hasExactSynonym>
    <obo:hasExactSynonym xml:lang="en">Calfee phenotype 2</obo:hasExactSynonym>
    <obo:hasDbXref>MESH:D012128</obo:hasDbXref>
    <obo:hasDbXref>UMLS:C0035222</obo:hasDbXref>
    <obo:source_pmid>25030514</obo:source_pmid>
    <owl:disjointWith rdf:resource="http://poi-kb.org/ards/ARDS_POI_03201"/>
    <rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="http://poi-kb.org/ards/ARDS_POI_03270"/>
    <poi:hasBiomarker rdf:resource="http://poi-kb.org/ards/ARDS_POI_03271"/>
    <poi:hasBiomarker rdf:resource="http://poi-kb.org/ards/ARDS_POI_03205"/>
    <poi:hasBiomarker rdf:resource="http://poi-kb.org/ards/ARDS_POI_03206"/>
    <poi:hasBiomarker rdf:resource="http://poi-kb.org/ards/ARDS_POI_03282"/>
    <poi:hasBiomarker rdf:resource="http://poi-kb.org/ards/ARDS_POI_03283"/>
    <rdfs:comment xml:lang="en">Hyperinflammatory subphenotype may benefit from HIGHER PEEP strategy. Also shows differential response to simvastatin (beneficial) and corticosteroids (dexamethasone, DEXA-ARDS convergence).</rdfs:comment>
    <rdfs:comment xml:lang="en">IL-6 markedly elevated in hyperinflammatory ARDS. &gt;400 pg/mL threshold.</rdfs:comment>
    <rdfs:comment xml:lang="en">IL-8 elevated; included in parsimonious 3-variable classifier.</rdfs:comment>
    <rdfs:comment xml:lang="en">Conservative fluid management shows mortality benefit in hyperinflammatory subphenotype (HTE: Calfee 2018 ARDS Network reanalysis).</rdfs:comment>
    <rdfs:comment xml:lang="en">Greater steroid benefit expected in hyperinflammatory subphenotype (anti-inflammatory mechanism aligns with phenotype biology; DEXA-ARDS converges with RECOVERY evidence).</rdfs:comment>
    <rdfs:comment xml:lang="en">Mortality ~2.5x higher than hypoinflammatory in matched cohorts. More vasopressor-dependent shock, metabolic acidosis, multi-organ failure. Shorter ventilator-free days.</rdfs:comment>
    <rdfs:comment xml:lang="en">Protein C LOW in hyperinflammatory — procoagulant state, endothelial activation. Part of parsimonious classifier.</rdfs:comment>
    <rdfs:comment xml:lang="en">Low bicarbonate = metabolic acidosis. Part of parsimonious classifier.</rdfs:comment>
    <rdfs:comment xml:lang="en">High EVLWI associated with hyperinflammatory subphenotype — supports conservative fluid strategy in this phenotype.</rdfs:comment>
    <poi:hasDifferentialResponse rdf:resource="http://poi-kb.org/ards/ARDS_POI_03284"/>
    <poi:hasDifferentialResponse rdf:resource="http://poi-kb.org/ards/ARDS_POI_01006"/>
    <poi:hasClinicalOutcome rdf:resource="http://poi-kb.org/ards/ARDS_POI_03287"/>
  </rdf:Description>
